There’s just something about being unapologetically yourself that’s so wildly freeing. I experienced authentic joy when I was no longer bound by the opinions of others, when I chose peace over pleasing, and when I started to celebrate each and every morning God allowed me to be on this earth. 

The world we live in today is the perfect environment to cultivate anxiety in its most destructive form. “What if” and “worst case scenario” are waiting behind every corner. Our minds constantly race to the unknown, robbing us of the gift that living in the present moment so generously gives us. Humanity as a whole will never be immune to heart-wrenching, rock bottom moments.

Despite the pain we will inevitably experience, the moment we took our first breath, we were given a precious gift: perspective. On the other side of pain there is abundant joy. Life is 10% of what happens to us and 90% of how we respond to it. Despite the worst of circumstances, there is always simple moments to rejoice in. You see friend, pain doesn’t always have to be punishment. If we allow it to be, pain can leverage us into a shift of perspective. One that opens our eyes to all the things we have to be grateful for that we otherwise overlook. Joy is found in the sheer beauty of a sunny day, the symphony orchestrated from the sound of laughter, the phone calls with a friend that turns into hours of vulnerable and honest conversation, watching the sky paint a masterpiece of vibrant colors while the sun goes down, and pausing long enough to hear the words “I love you”, from the one you care about the most. 

The accolades we acquire, the possessions we have, the “success” we work so hard for can all bring happiness. But the thing about happiness, is that it’s circumstantial and temporary. But joy, true authentic joy.. that’s an eternal gift from Jesus and absolutely no one can take it from you. So chin up, my love, this pain is only temporary. Joy is just on the horizon, you just have to open your heart to receive it.

I know life isn’t easy, friend. You may find yourself in a season of heartache with no end in sight. There’s burdens you’re carrying so well in silence, though each day you feel like you’re failing. But I promise you, it does get better. Take it one single day at a time, choose to be present, and do the best you can with what you have. Journal each good moment of the day, no matter how silly it may feel, and praise Jesus for them. Before you know it, you’ll start to see all the beauty, despite the mess and the simplest things will become what you appreciate most. There is joy, my love, though it looks different than before. Hope is promised to you and on the other side of it all, life will be far sweeter than you could’ve ever imagined.

Pride means something different for each and every person. For some, it’s a time of joy and unity and for others, it’s a time of confusion and division. I can’t sum up what pride means as a whole for each and every person, but I can define what pride means to me. 

When I think of pride, I think of my journey in life thus far. All of the heartbreak, the moments I spent asking why and what if? I think of the times I failed and the times I could’ve done better. I reflect back to a season of hopelessness, the shame I carried, and the times I wanted to end it all. But I also think of all healing, the growth, and the beautiful shift in perspective. All of the precious, simple, and magical moments I’ve had with my kids. And I think of friends and family who loved me when I couldn’t. 

For me, Pride isn’t just about celebrating who I love, but the journey I’ve been on to truly love myself. Pride is about reflecting where I’ve been so I can be proud where I am now. Pride is about seeing people just as they are, imperfections and flaws, and loving them anyways. It’s about giving people the space and freedom to be their most authentic self. Pride is about celebrating friends and family who have chosen to love me wholeheartedly, despite if they understand or agree with me. 

Pride is so much more than just a month to be celebrated exclusively for one community. It’s more than parades, colors on a flag, or hashtags on social media. 

Pride is about loving yourself unapologetically, being confident in who you and allowing that love to overflow and pour out on the people around you. 

When you wear the Megan 2: Pride edition sunglasses, my hope is for you to be reminded of how far you’ve come, to love yourself just as you are, and to be unapologetically authentic. Pride isn’t just about celebrating who you love, but celebrating the journey of loving yourself.

After 30 days, 18 doctors, 5 rooms, and 2 hospitals… I’m happy to share I’m finally out of the hospital and on the road to recovery ❤️

Honestly, im still trying to fully comprehend that just over a month ago I was in a coma in the ICU, fully septic, lungs filled with fluid, and recovering from a heart attack after coding twice. I wish I had the words to summarize all of my thoughts and emotions, but one thing I know for certain is the overwhelming gratitude I have for my brilliant team of doctors and specialists. They literally saved my life and their dedication to my care ultimately lead to a diagnosis and treatment plan.

As my journey to recovery and rehabilitation begins, I can’t help but to sit in awe of how far God has brought me. There were many tears, moments of defeat and frustration, days of just wanting to give up, and sleepless nights of asking why. But through it all, Jesus kept me so near and He blessed me with the most amazing support system. I couldn’t have made it through without my dad, big sister, and Fre. But the true MVP of this all is my mommy. She was my  ROCK through everything. She advocated fiercely for me, never left my side, and refused to take no for an answer. She never gave up and truly is the reason I had the very best care and doctors possible. She held me when I cried, made me laugh even the most chaotic situations, and kept me in check when I was acting a little crazy 🙃 She truly deserves the mom of the century award. 

Thank you SO SO MUCH to everyone who has reached out, for all the prayers, love, and support that’s been poured out over myself and my babies. It truly means more to me than words could possibly express. 

There’s still a journey to recovery ahead, but I firmly believe the very best is yet to come ❤️

Ps- this was caused by undiagnosed health conditions, never got the 💉 for those asking.
